CONFUSION, TOWNSEND! I have diſcovered the plot—I have got a clue to the whole matter. I am, I perceive, a very catſpaw. I am made the convenient cloak to conceal the paſſion of another. Yes, TOWNSEND, I ſaw CARLISLE at the very fartheſt end of DE GREY's garden in earneſt converſation with LUCIA: at my approach he turned into a different walk, and went into the houſe. I overtook the guilty fair one, and caught her in the very act of reading ELOISA to ABELARD; which is as much as to ſay, if I can't talk with him, I can at leaſt write a letter to him;

and I dare ſay they do correſpond: every body in this family ſcribbles, and I don't at all doubt but there is fine flouriſhing penwork going forward between LUCIA and CARLISLE. As to the firſt, I only walked quickly by her, without deigning to ſpeak, and I pulled off my hat with unuſual reſpect, as much as to ſay—Oh, oh, my young lady, have I caught you! I ſhall repeat the ſame behaviour when I meet her again, and then it is impoſſible ſhe ſhould miſtake my meaning. With reſpect to the Captain, whom I honour as a friend and gentleman, in every other matter, his life is not worth ſixpence, for he muſt as ſurely die this night, as that he inſulted me this day; or elſe he muſt injure me ſtill more, by taking me off. I only write this to you, TOWNSEND, juſt to account for any delay in my correſpondence, ſhould it be my fate

inſtead of his. In that caſe I deſire you will be at the breaking open my will, becauſe you are mentioned therein, by
